<h2>
    Linear Gradients
</h2>
<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(**angle**, **color1**, **color2**, ...);</code></pre>
<p>
    Linear Gradients work in one direction and must have at 
    least two(2) colors (like red to green). It then transitions 
    from one color to the next using a gradient, and moving in the 
    direction defined by <code>**angle</code>. 
</p>
<p>
    The <code>**angle</code> argument is optional. If no angle is supplied, 
    then it defaults to "to bottom".
</p>
    
<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(red, green);</code></pre>

<p class="text-white" style="margin-left: 30px;background-image: linear-gradient(red, green);">
    Gradient Red to Green Top to Bottom
</p>
<h3>
    Angle Options
</h3>
<h3>
    top/bottom & left/right
</h3>
<p>
    The gradient angle can compose of the word <code>to</code> and up to two more words, 
    one indicating vertical position (top bottom) and the other horizontal (left right). 
    The ordering does not matter, (<code>to top left</code> is the same as <code>to left top</code>). 
</p>
<p>
    Both directions do not have to be specified either, for example: <code>to bottom</code> or <code>to left</code>. 
</p>

<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(to left, red, green);</code></pre>

<p class="text-white" style="margin-left: 30px;background-image: linear-gradient(to left, red, green);">
    to left
</p>

<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(to bottom left, red, green);</code></pre>
<p class="text-white" style="margin-left: 30px;background-image: 
linear-gradient(
    to bottom left, red, green
    );">
    to bottom left
</p>

<h3>
    Using DegreesÂ°
</h3>
<p>
    Degrees can be used as well, with the number and then <code>deg</code> for degrees. 
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(45deg, red, black);</code></pre>

<p class="text-white" style="margin-left: 30px;background-image: 
linear-gradient(
    45deg, red, black
    );">
    45deg, red, black
</p>
<p>
    Certain degrees match the <code>to</code> values:
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-css">    to top = 0deg
    to bottom = 180deg
    to left = 270deg
    to right = 90deg
</code></pre>

<h3>
    Custom Stop Position 
</h3>
<p>
    The gradient can be radically customized with custom break or stop points, 
    which explicitly state where each gradient ends. A length or a percentage <code>%</code> 
    can be used for stop points.
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(45deg, red 0%, orange 25%, yellow 50%, green 75%, blue 100%);
</code></pre>

<p style="margin-left: 35px; background: linear-gradient(45deg, red 0%, orange 25%, yellow 50%, green 75%, blue 100%);">
    Custom Stops
</p>

<p>
    The end stops can also be specified:
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-css">linear-gradient(45deg, red 0% 10%, orange 10% 50%, yellow 50% 75%, green 75% 90%, blue 90% 100%);
</code></pre>
<p style="margin-left: 35px; background: linear-gradient(45deg, red 0% 10%, orange 10% 50%, yellow 50% 75%, green 75% 90%, blue 90% 100%);">
    Custom Stops
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-css">background: linear-gradient(45deg, black 25%, yellow 25% 50%, black 50% 75%, yellow 75% 100%);</code></pre>
